1
00:01:55,550 --> 00:01:58,470
What do you say
we get ourselves some turkey, partner?

2
00:01:59,550 --> 00:02:00,950
They're here!

3
00:02:01,590 --> 00:02:05,710
Now remember,
I want you kids to be especially nice to Danny.

4
00:02:05,790 --> 00:02:09,390
- Why should we?
- Because I say so, that's why.

5
00:02:09,550 --> 00:02:11,990
- Don't touch that pie.
- I'm hungry!

6
00:02:12,150 --> 00:02:14,550
Hungry? You don't know what hunger is.

7
00:02:14,710 --> 00:02:17,110
You want to know about hunger,
talk to the Russians.

8
00:02:17,270 --> 00:02:21,030
- They'll tell you about hunger.
- Grace has Russia on the brain.

9
00:02:21,150 --> 00:02:24,230
But they're so grand!

10
00:02:25,390 --> 00:02:29,830
Now, Grace was your mom's best friend
back in England...

11
00:02:29,950 --> 00:02:32,790
...and she's a little nuts, but she's nice.

12
00:02:33,790 --> 00:02:38,110
Her husband is a professor of something.

13
00:02:39,430 --> 00:02:42,270
There will be a lot of kids in there
for you to play with, too.

14
00:02:42,390 --> 00:02:45,830
And I don't want you kids teasing Danny.
Do you understand me?

15
00:02:45,950 --> 00:02:47,510
- What's the matter with him?
- Liz's boy.

16
00:02:47,670 --> 00:02:49,110
She died last year.

17
00:02:49,230 --> 00:02:52,990
- He found her body.
- That is just so awful.

18
00:02:53,230 --> 00:02:54,630
He's very shy.

19
00:02:55,430 --> 00:02:57,190
See? He is a retard.

20
00:02:57,310 --> 00:03:01,070
What did I say about using that word
in this house, William Swan?

21
00:03:01,150 --> 00:03:02,630
What did I say?

22
00:03:06,150 --> 00:03:09,150
- You going to be okay, partner?
- Yeah, I'm okay.

23
00:03:09,870 --> 00:03:12,110
You want a blindfold
or a cigarette or something?

24
00:03:12,190 --> 00:03:13,630
- No.
- You sure?

25
00:03:14,230 --> 00:03:16,150
Okay. Ring the doorbell.

26
00:03:29,830 --> 00:03:31,150
Hey, sweetheart.

27
00:03:31,550 --> 00:03:33,710
Danny, welcome!

28
00:03:34,430 --> 00:03:37,110
- Look at how big you are!
- Yeah.

29
00:03:37,190 --> 00:03:40,110
And don't you look like your mother!

30
00:03:40,830 --> 00:03:42,870
When's the flag on that butterball gonna pop?

31
00:03:42,990 --> 00:03:44,070
- Professor.
- Doctor.

32
00:03:44,150 --> 00:03:45,630
- How you doing?
- Can't complain.

33
00:03:45,750 --> 00:03:48,670
Why don't you and the kids watch
some football with Danny?

34
00:03:48,830 --> 00:03:51,110
Give her the cake. There you go.

35
00:03:51,230 --> 00:03:52,510
Thank you, Danny!

36
00:03:52,830 --> 00:03:54,870
- Happy Thanksgiving.
- Welcome.

37
00:03:55,190 --> 00:03:56,950
Let's get you a drink.

38
00:04:02,550 --> 00:04:03,510
You moved.

39
00:04:03,590 --> 00:04:05,350
Keep your arms still!

40
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:10,870
I miss Liz so much.

41
00:04:11,230 --> 00:04:14,430
I'll see something on the TV,
and I'll want to call her and tell her.

42
00:04:14,550 --> 00:04:15,990
Yeah, I know what you mean.

43
00:04:16,110 --> 00:04:17,150
Hank, would you mind?

44
00:04:17,270 --> 00:04:18,870
No, not at all.

45
00:04:19,430 --> 00:04:22,310
I can't imagine how Danny must miss her.

46
00:04:22,710 --> 00:04:24,790
How can he understand a thing like that?

47
00:04:24,910 --> 00:04:27,750
The shrink on the base says
eventually he'll come around.

48
00:04:27,870 --> 00:04:30,390
Yeah, if nothing else, he's resilient.

49
00:04:30,910 --> 00:04:34,870
Did you know that the domestic turkey
is unable to procreate naturally?

50
00:04:34,990 --> 00:04:37,790
I thought only Konrad used that excuse.

51
00:04:37,870 --> 00:04:42,470
We've genetically bred these poor birds
to have such large white-meat breasts...

52
00:04:42,590 --> 00:04:45,670
...that it's impossible for them to copulate.

53
00:04:45,790 --> 00:04:48,030
- Anything for white meat.
- How do turkeys do it?

54
00:04:48,150 --> 00:04:50,550
Test tubes. The way we'd do it, if we were smart.

55
00:04:50,670 --> 00:04:53,190
Richard is such a romantic.

56
00:04:53,950 --> 00:04:57,270
Hank, I'm so happy that you and Danny
are going to be close by.

57
00:04:57,430 --> 00:05:01,230
We're not. I signed on to
a NATO hospital outside of London.

58
00:05:01,350 --> 00:05:05,150
- You did?
- You know, Liz's family's back there.

59
00:05:05,510 --> 00:05:07,030
I figured that'd be good for Danny.

60
00:05:07,150 --> 00:05:09,590
- When do you leave?
- A couple weeks.

61
00:05:21,470 --> 00:05:23,550
We'll expect you next year.

62
00:06:15,510 --> 00:06:18,190
Hold on. Let's put her on the couch over there.

63
00:06:18,270 --> 00:06:20,990
- Okay.
- Don't push.

64
00:06:21,110 --> 00:06:23,990
- You kids go outside and play!
- It's dark outside.

65
00:06:24,110 --> 00:06:25,710
Take a flashlight!

66
00:06:26,910 --> 00:06:29,750
- Can you hold on until the doctor gets here?
- Hank's a doctor.

67
00:06:29,910 --> 00:06:33,230
- I'd prefer a sober one.
- Thanks for the vote of confidence.

68
00:06:33,350 --> 00:06:34,590
Have you ever done this before?

69
00:06:34,710 --> 00:06:37,030
We don't deliver many babies at the base.

70
00:06:37,150 --> 00:06:39,110
We can hang on till that ambulance gets here.

71
00:06:39,230 --> 00:06:42,630
- I don't think so.
- What do you mean, "I don't think so"?

72
00:06:42,750 --> 00:06:46,150
What she means, Richard,
is that this baby is hot to be born.

73
00:06:46,270 --> 00:06:48,950
Nothing we do is gonna change that.
Hold her knee up here.

74
00:06:49,070 --> 00:06:51,990
- I'm sorry, I've got to push!
- Where the hell is the ambulance?

75
00:06:52,070 --> 00:06:53,790
If you gotta push, push. Push.

76
00:06:55,990 --> 00:06:58,430
Okay. Breathe, Gracie.

77
00:06:58,550 --> 00:07:00,510
Okay, hold on. Gracie, listen to me.

78
00:07:00,670 --> 00:07:01,790
You have done this before.

79
00:07:01,950 --> 00:07:04,790
We gotta give this baby a little bit of help.

80
00:07:05,470 --> 00:07:07,030
Push again. Ready?

81
00:07:07,150 --> 00:07:10,790
All right. Ready. One, two, three. Push.

82
00:07:11,110 --> 00:07:13,910
- Push, Grace.
- A little bit more. That a girl.

83
00:07:14,150 --> 00:07:16,070
All right. Okay. Breathe.

84
00:07:18,030 --> 00:07:19,470
- Son of a bitch.
- What?

85
00:07:19,550 --> 00:07:20,790
We got a little problem here.

86
00:07:20,870 --> 00:07:22,870
What do you mean, "a little problem"?

87
00:07:22,950 --> 00:07:25,430
- Nothing I can't handle, all right?
- What?

88
00:07:25,950 --> 00:07:27,630
The umbilical cord might be wrapped...

89
00:07:27,710 --> 00:07:29,590
What do you mean, it might be wrapped?

90
00:07:29,670 --> 00:07:31,830
It might be wrapped around the baby's neck.

91
00:07:31,950 --> 00:07:33,670
Isn't there anything you can do about it?

92
00:07:33,790 --> 00:07:36,470
I don't know, Richard. What do turkeys do?

93
00:07:36,590 --> 00:07:39,830
Of course we can do something.
It's a common problem.

94
00:07:41,470 --> 00:07:43,670
You! Get out of here!

95
00:07:47,270 --> 00:07:48,790
Do what he says, son.

96
00:07:48,910 --> 00:07:51,230
Breathe, Gracie, breathe.

97
00:07:52,990 --> 00:07:55,550
- The retard's in there.
- Let me see!

98
00:07:55,870 --> 00:07:57,590
No, wait. Come here a second.

99
00:07:57,710 --> 00:07:59,550
Let me see your hands. Are they clean?

100
00:07:59,670 --> 00:08:01,870
All right. Listen to me. Listen good, okay?

101
00:08:01,950 --> 00:08:04,550
I want you to help me out.
I want you to reach in there...

102
00:08:04,670 --> 00:08:05,910
Inside my wife?

103
00:08:06,390 --> 00:08:10,630
Look, my hands are too big.
I'm too damn drunk. His hands are smaller.

104
00:08:10,750 --> 00:08:13,910
- He can tell me what the problem is.
- Let him do it!

105
00:08:14,030 --> 00:08:17,270
- Can you do this for me?
- What are they doing in there?

106
00:08:17,350 --> 00:08:20,950
Can you do this for me?
Okay. Now, there's a baby in there.

107
00:08:21,990 --> 00:08:23,670
I'll explain later.

108
00:08:25,950 --> 00:08:29,950
I want you to reach inside really slowly,
very gently, with one hand, okay?

109
00:08:30,230 --> 00:08:33,950
Go on. Put your hand in there.
Slowly, slowly. There you go.

110
00:08:34,070 --> 00:08:37,550
Okay. Can you feel the baby?
Can you feel the baby's head?

111
00:08:37,670 --> 00:08:40,430
- I don't believe this!
- Shut up, Richard!

112
00:08:40,710 --> 00:08:42,870
Can you feel its neck?

113
00:08:42,950 --> 00:08:45,110
All right. I want you to find the umbilical cord.

114
00:08:45,190 --> 00:08:48,230
It's like a wet rope,
like the time we made that trailer hitch...

115
00:08:48,350 --> 00:08:50,710
...and it's wrapped around the baby's neck.

116
00:08:50,830 --> 00:08:53,390
I want you to uncurl it so the baby can be born.

117
00:08:53,470 --> 00:08:57,270
- Can you feel it?
- He doesn't know what he's doing!

118
00:08:57,750 --> 00:08:59,790
Keep trying, son. Come on.

119
00:09:00,270 --> 00:09:01,910
- Keep trying.
- This is insane.

120
00:09:01,990 --> 00:09:04,630
Think. You got it yet?

121
00:09:05,470 --> 00:09:07,950
You do? You got it? You got it. Okay, good.

122
00:09:08,030 --> 00:09:09,590
Now I want you to put your fingers...

123
00:09:09,750 --> 00:09:12,270
...between the umbilical cord
and the baby's neck...

124
00:09:12,390 --> 00:09:15,030
...so that when you uncurl it,
the baby can be born, okay?

125
00:09:15,150 --> 00:09:18,350
All right. Can you do that for me?
Do it for me now, son. Come on.

126
00:09:18,510 --> 00:09:22,430
- Just do what he says, son.
- Okay. You got it? You got hold of it?

127
00:09:22,550 --> 00:09:24,790
Okay. Uncurl it.

128
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:26,870
Gentle. Slow.

129
00:09:27,630 --> 00:09:28,790
Okay.

130
00:09:29,310 --> 00:09:31,350
You think you got it done? You do?

131
00:09:31,470 --> 00:09:33,070
- It's away from the baby's neck?
- Yeah.

132
00:09:33,150 --> 00:09:35,630
Okay, now take your hand out gently.

133
00:09:36,510 --> 00:09:38,750
Okay, Gracie, get ready to push, okay?

134
00:09:38,870 --> 00:09:41,270
One, two, three, push.

135
00:09:42,510 --> 00:09:43,990
- Push.
- Push, Grace.

136
00:09:44,110 --> 00:09:46,270
Okay, Gracie, it's crowning.

137
00:09:46,430 --> 00:09:48,350
Take a breath. One more. A big one.

138
00:09:48,470 --> 00:09:52,550
- One, two, three, push!
- Push, Grace!

139
00:09:54,910 --> 00:09:56,230
- Push!
- Okay!

140
00:09:58,070 --> 00:09:59,630
It's a girl.

141
00:10:06,750 --> 00:10:08,350
Look at her!

142
00:10:09,910 --> 00:10:11,510
A beautiful girl.

143
00:10:13,870 --> 00:10:15,350
Not so bad!

144
00:10:15,870 --> 00:10:17,830
A beautiful girl.

145
00:10:20,230 --> 00:10:21,630
Let's give her to her mama, son.

146
00:10:21,790 --> 00:10:23,230
Careful. There you go.

147
00:10:32,750 --> 00:10:34,470
Good job, son.

148
00:10:38,470 --> 00:10:39,470
Anna.

149
00:10:40,430 --> 00:10:42,390
Her name is Anna.

150
00:10:46,310 --> 00:10:47,950
I'm gonna marry her.

151
00:11:45,310 --> 00:11:47,510
I thought you and me were gonna live together!

152
00:11:47,590 --> 00:11:48,710
What made you think that?

153
00:11:48,830 --> 00:11:52,030
Probably when you said,
"When you get here, we'll live together. "

154
00:11:52,150 --> 00:11:53,550
Here. Come on. Hurry up.

155
00:11:53,630 --> 00:11:56,150
- These guys charge by the hour.
- I'm not crazy, am I?

156
00:11:56,270 --> 00:11:58,830
That was the plan, wasn't it?
I come here. I get a job.

157
00:11:58,910 --> 00:12:01,350
- We share a place. Right?
- I wrote you not to come.

158
00:12:01,470 --> 00:12:04,150
I was on the road, wasn't I, coming here?

159
00:12:04,670 --> 00:12:05,710
What did you say?

160
00:12:05,790 --> 00:12:08,590
- I'm moving to New York.
- What's in New York?

161
00:12:08,670 --> 00:12:10,710
- William.
- William?

162
00:12:11,030 --> 00:12:13,430
William of New York?
Who's that? Like Joan of Arc?

163
00:12:13,550 --> 00:12:14,870
Would you please be careful?

164
00:12:14,950 --> 00:12:18,430
- I thought you loved me.
- Really? What made you think that?

165
00:12:19,190 --> 00:12:21,750
Probably when you said, "I love you. "

166
00:12:23,430 --> 00:12:27,510
That's really sweet, Danny,
but you're so damn literal.

167
00:12:27,910 --> 00:12:30,790
It's a wonderful quality, okay? Don't lose it.

168
00:12:31,390 --> 00:12:32,350
Thank you.

169
00:12:32,710 --> 00:12:35,830
What am I going to do now?
Where am I going to live, Sarah?

170
00:12:35,950 --> 00:12:39,230
I'll tell you what.
I'll sublet this apartment to you.

171
00:12:39,750 --> 00:12:41,870
- How much?
- $1,600.

172
00:12:42,270 --> 00:12:44,030
- A month?
- Yeah.

173
00:12:44,430 --> 00:12:47,230
Okay. $1,550, but I can't go any lower than that.

174
00:12:47,350 --> 00:12:50,670
There's a waiting list a mile long.
Take it or leave it.

175
00:12:52,870 --> 00:12:56,150
No, not that box! Goddamn it!

176
00:13:06,870 --> 00:13:09,630
I am never, ever going to fall in love again!

177
00:13:10,070 --> 00:13:11,310
Good luck.

178
00:13:44,830 --> 00:13:46,910
I don't need nobody.

179
00:13:47,830 --> 00:13:51,310
- Tambini said that with the letter I'd get a job.
- Well, he was wrong.

180
00:13:51,390 --> 00:13:53,990
- I've come all the way from London!
- You got a green card?

181
00:13:54,110 --> 00:13:55,350
Yeah, I'm an American citizen.

182
00:13:55,510 --> 00:13:57,750
I got 15 kids that are waiting to apprentice.

183
00:13:57,870 --> 00:14:00,750
- I'm not an apprentice.
- What can I tell you, kid?

184
00:14:01,030 --> 00:14:03,590
I don't have the money.
If I did, I would hire 10 of you.

185
00:14:03,710 --> 00:14:05,950
I mean, look how much work I got to do here.

186
00:14:06,070 --> 00:14:08,950
- Mel, you got to move that to the left!
- Okay, boss!

187
00:14:09,030 --> 00:14:10,790
I could do that, sir. I'm the best!

188
00:14:12,270 --> 00:14:13,750
You're the best?

189
00:14:15,390 --> 00:14:16,790
Call me in a week.

190
00:14:41,550 --> 00:14:43,990
But the way you talk, where are you from?

191
00:14:44,110 --> 00:14:45,510
I'm from here.

192
00:14:46,910 --> 00:14:48,950
I was born on an Army base outside of town...

193
00:14:49,070 --> 00:14:51,510
...but I moved to England with my dad
when I was five.

194
00:14:51,630 --> 00:14:54,510
- Is that right?
- He died last year, so...

195
00:14:56,030 --> 00:14:58,830
You work delivery and the rent goes down.

196
00:15:01,150 --> 00:15:04,150
Actually that might be useful,
because I'm waiting on a job.

197
00:15:04,310 --> 00:15:06,950
- What do you do?
- Mosaics, you know?

198
00:15:07,070 --> 00:15:10,590
- I work with tiles.
- Is there a call for that?

199
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:14,070
No, not enough. It's a dying art, really.

200
00:15:14,190 --> 00:15:16,670
They use computers
to design mosaics nowadays.

201
00:15:16,790 --> 00:15:18,670
It's like baking, you know?

202
00:15:18,830 --> 00:15:23,550
Now it's all plastic,
plastic wrap and advertisement.

203
00:15:23,670 --> 00:15:28,190
Actually, I noticed downstairs,
in front of the shop, you have red granite floors.

204
00:15:28,310 --> 00:15:31,150
Pretty rare, from Italy, which is where I trained.

205
00:15:31,230 --> 00:15:32,750
I wouldn't know.

206
00:15:34,270 --> 00:15:35,790
This is it.

207
00:15:39,190 --> 00:15:40,950
No smoking, no parties.

208
00:15:42,110 --> 00:15:43,950
The girl before you here...

209
00:15:44,670 --> 00:15:46,150
...she had parties.

210
00:15:46,630 --> 00:15:47,750
Really?

211
00:15:49,470 --> 00:15:51,470
- Smells good.
- Here you are.

212
00:15:52,910 --> 00:15:54,550
Do you ride a bike?

213
00:15:54,710 --> 00:15:57,110
- Yeah, I ride a bike.
- That's good.

214
00:15:59,110 --> 00:16:00,350
Thank you.

215
00:16:34,390 --> 00:16:37,470
Excuse me.
Do you know where Olmsted Street is?

216
00:16:37,630 --> 00:16:40,590
Olmsted Street. Thanks for your help.

217
00:16:58,950 --> 00:17:00,190
Who is it?

218
00:17:03,710 --> 00:17:07,670
I'm sorry. I'm lost.
I'm trying to deliver this cake.

219
00:17:10,710 --> 00:17:11,830
Where to?

220
00:17:13,310 --> 00:17:16,830
That's all right. I'm looking for Olmsted Street.

221
00:17:17,030 --> 00:17:19,190
Wait! Anna?

222
00:17:19,310 --> 00:17:22,110
We'll be back later, Mother.
I thought you were coming with us.

223
00:17:22,190 --> 00:17:23,830
I can't. I changed my mind.

224
00:17:23,950 --> 00:17:26,670
- I won't let anything happen to you.
- Go with her. Have fun!

225
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:28,590
- I don't want to!
- Don't be silly.

226
00:17:28,670 --> 00:17:30,470
I'm not being silly. I can't skate.

227
00:17:33,750 --> 00:17:36,950
It's easy. I'll show you how.
I bet he can skate. Can you?

228
00:17:37,310 --> 00:17:40,270
- Yeah, I can skate.
- See? Anyone can do it.

229
00:17:40,390 --> 00:17:42,750
No, I'll just stay here with Mother.

230
00:17:43,150 --> 00:17:44,510
Suit yourself. I'm late.

231
00:17:48,590 --> 00:17:51,390
Just make sure to tell Irene
that I'll baby-sit Lily tonight.

232
00:17:51,470 --> 00:17:54,270
And make sure Mother
takes her medicine at 2:00 and 4:00.

233
00:17:54,350 --> 00:17:57,430
- All right.
- Can I help you with something?

234
00:17:59,190 --> 00:18:01,910
This gentleman is looking for Olmsted Street.

235
00:18:01,990 --> 00:18:03,510
Olmsted Street.

236
00:18:03,710 --> 00:18:05,830
Okay, go up to the corner, take a left.

237
00:18:05,950 --> 00:18:09,710
When you get to the second stop sign,
you pass a drugstore to the right...

238
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:20,830
...go up to the second stop sign...

239
00:18:20,990 --> 00:18:23,350
...take a sharp right, and then left at the church.

240
00:18:23,470 --> 00:18:25,430
Did you understand all that?

241
00:18:30,150 --> 00:18:31,470
Yeah.

242
00:18:40,030 --> 00:18:41,950
<i>You said that? Five years old?</i>

243
00:18:42,070 --> 00:18:43,190
<i>"I'm going to marry her. "</i>

244
00:18:43,310 --> 00:18:46,550
I know, my father told me that stupid story
millions of times.

245
00:18:46,670 --> 00:18:48,710
- Now you meet her.
- It's kismet.

246
00:18:48,830 --> 00:18:50,870
- Yeah. What's that?
- Fate.

247
00:18:51,070 --> 00:18:53,910
Anna Swan, what a beautiful name.

248
00:18:54,110 --> 00:18:56,950
Vicious birds, swans, vicious.

249
00:18:58,590 --> 00:18:59,950
What do you know about them?

250
00:19:00,030 --> 00:19:03,110
Once they drowned a boy
in Boston in some park.

251
00:19:03,750 --> 00:19:05,270
No. I mean the family.

252
00:19:05,870 --> 00:19:09,470
Yes, they're very nice people.
They come in here sometimes.

253
00:19:10,070 --> 00:19:12,230
Blind girl, she has a sweet tooth.

254
00:19:12,350 --> 00:19:14,950
She loves raspberry tarts.

255
00:19:15,350 --> 00:19:17,070
The mother is sick...

256
00:19:17,470 --> 00:19:20,870
...and the one called Anna
spends a lot of time with her.

257
00:19:20,990 --> 00:19:23,390
- Does she live there?
- I don't think so. Why?

258
00:19:23,590 --> 00:19:27,110
- He's in love with her.
- No, no. I'm not in love with her.

259
00:19:27,470 --> 00:19:29,870
When you least want it, love happens.

260
00:19:30,310 --> 00:19:31,830
Like appendicitis.

261
00:19:31,950 --> 00:19:34,870
<i>I promise you, this is not love. I know love.</i>

262
00:19:35,070 --> 00:19:38,150
<i>No, when I fall in love,
it's like an alien invasion in my body.</i>

263
00:19:38,270 --> 00:19:39,590
<i>I turn out like a complete idiot.</i>

264
00:19:39,710 --> 00:19:43,630
<i>I won't say it won't happen to me again,
but it won't be this time.</i>

265
00:19:48,870 --> 00:19:50,750
And what's the event?

266
00:19:51,630 --> 00:19:55,190
She didn't say.
She just called up and ordered the cake.

267
00:19:55,270 --> 00:19:56,830
- Nothing written on it?
- No.

268
00:19:56,950 --> 00:19:58,550
- Nothing?
- Nothing.

269
00:19:59,550 --> 00:20:00,590
You don't want to take it?

270
00:20:00,670 --> 00:20:04,510
No, I'll take it. It's my chance to meet them.

271
00:20:05,150 --> 00:20:08,430
- Yes, coincidence.
- Exactly!

272
00:20:08,510 --> 00:20:09,710
I can deliver the cake.

273
00:20:09,790 --> 00:20:12,150
I recognize the house,
see the name on the door...

274
00:20:12,230 --> 00:20:13,350
...introduce myself.

275
00:20:13,470 --> 00:20:16,150
This is your chance to meet the young lady.

276
00:20:18,230 --> 00:20:19,230
Yeah.

277
00:20:19,710 --> 00:20:20,670
Anna.

278
00:20:21,750 --> 00:20:25,870
What is she? She's, you know,
not an astronaut or anything, is she?

279
00:20:25,950 --> 00:20:27,630
- She's just a woman, right?
- Correct.

280
00:20:27,710 --> 00:20:29,710
Right. The world's full of women.

281
00:20:29,830 --> 00:20:32,630
- More than men.
- Exactly! No big deal.

282
00:20:33,190 --> 00:20:35,670
I helped deliver her.
What's, you know, the big deal?

283
00:20:35,790 --> 00:20:38,310
Two normal people being introduced.

284
00:20:38,430 --> 00:20:42,550
Take all the mystery out of this situation,
and then we can just be friends.

285
00:20:43,430 --> 00:20:44,670
Right.

286
00:20:45,350 --> 00:20:47,550
Okay. Here. Give me the cake.

287
00:20:49,070 --> 00:20:50,670
Hi. I'm Danny Kowalski.

288
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:55,150
I delivered you,
and now I'm delivering you a cake.

289
00:20:58,230 --> 00:21:00,110
Hi. Remember me?

290
00:21:00,990 --> 00:21:02,590
I'm Danny Kowalski.

291
00:21:02,990 --> 00:21:04,670
I remember you.

292
00:21:05,750 --> 00:21:07,230
I really remember you.

293
00:21:07,870 --> 00:21:10,550
It's me, Danny Kowalski. Remember?

294
00:21:12,670 --> 00:21:13,870
Hi.

295
00:21:14,150 --> 00:21:15,390
I'm Danny.

296
00:21:17,390 --> 00:21:18,790
- Hi!
- Hi, honey.

297
00:21:18,910 --> 00:21:20,150
I'm glad you're here.

298
00:21:34,190 --> 00:21:35,310
My God.

299
00:21:37,470 --> 00:21:40,310
- You shouldn't move.
- Here, I'll put this... Is this cold?

300
00:21:41,710 --> 00:21:44,070
- Now that blood will never come out.
- What happened?

301
00:21:44,190 --> 00:21:46,950
- The delivery boy fell off his bike.
- I'm all right, really.

302
00:21:47,070 --> 00:21:49,790
- I have your cake somewhere.
- That must be the cake I ordered.

303
00:21:49,910 --> 00:21:50,830
What's the occasion?

304
00:21:50,910 --> 00:21:53,750
- Are you okay?
- He'll probably sue.

305
00:21:54,230 --> 00:21:55,550
- You think so?
- I would.

306
00:21:55,670 --> 00:21:57,630
- I'll call an ambulance.
- No!

307
00:21:57,790 --> 00:21:59,710
- Keep still, you idiot!
- I'm all right.

308
00:21:59,790 --> 00:22:02,030
No. Really. Thank you. I'm all right.

309
00:22:02,230 --> 00:22:03,390
I'm fine.

310
00:22:06,870 --> 00:22:08,630
Hello. My name's Danny.

311
00:22:08,870 --> 00:22:10,310
Danny Kowalski.

312
00:22:12,030 --> 00:22:13,110
Oh, no.

313
00:22:13,470 --> 00:22:15,270
Here. Watch his head.

314
00:22:15,870 --> 00:22:18,910
- Give him room. Just give him some space.
- Let's get him inside.

315
00:22:32,550 --> 00:22:33,630
Hello.

316
00:22:35,310 --> 00:22:36,510
No, wait.

317
00:22:37,510 --> 00:22:38,990
Stop screaming!

318
00:22:59,870 --> 00:23:02,430
Anna, would you fetch that for me?

319
00:23:04,990 --> 00:23:08,750
- Billy, come out of the refrigerator.
- Where's that beer I bought?

320
00:23:08,870 --> 00:23:10,590
- You drank it, Billy.
- Hello.

321
00:23:10,710 --> 00:23:13,590
Daniel! There you are!

322
00:23:15,550 --> 00:23:18,470
- Are you feeling better?
- Much better, thank you.

323
00:23:18,870 --> 00:23:20,190
- Everybody...
- Hi.

324
00:23:20,310 --> 00:23:21,430
Listen.

325
00:23:25,350 --> 00:23:28,070
This is the man-child...

326
00:23:30,390 --> 00:23:33,070
...who thrust these very hands...

327
00:23:34,070 --> 00:23:37,110
...deep inside my reluctant womb...

328
00:23:39,790 --> 00:23:41,590
...and wrestled...

329
00:23:45,870 --> 00:23:49,510
...until he had wrenched life itself...

330
00:23:50,550 --> 00:23:52,830
...from my unwilling loins.

331
00:23:54,750 --> 00:23:57,150
- Come here!
- That's extraordinary!

332
00:23:57,310 --> 00:24:00,030
That's the retard! You're the retard.

333
00:24:01,030 --> 00:24:02,030
Here she is.

334
00:24:02,110 --> 00:24:04,470
- Anna, come here.
- I thought you were kidding.

335
00:24:05,550 --> 00:24:07,670
Isn't she magnificent?

336
00:24:07,790 --> 00:24:09,230
Mother, please.

337
00:24:09,710 --> 00:24:11,430
Hi. Nice to meet you.

338
00:24:12,030 --> 00:24:15,030
Last time we met, you were covered in afterbirth.

339
00:24:15,390 --> 00:24:19,350
- There's a line I bet you never heard before.
- Danny, this is Eric.

340
00:24:19,750 --> 00:24:22,550
Danny is the man responsible
for bringing me into the world.

341
00:24:22,630 --> 00:24:25,790
I'm very grateful.
It'd be a less interesting place without her.

342
00:24:25,910 --> 00:24:28,950
- Think nothing of it.
- Glad you're feeling better.

343
00:24:34,910 --> 00:24:36,670
- I'm Karen.
- Hi.

344
00:24:36,830 --> 00:24:38,950
- Is that your baby?
- Right.

345
00:24:42,870 --> 00:24:45,150
- Hello.
- Can you bring the baby in here, please?

346
00:24:45,270 --> 00:24:47,150
- Why'd you fire her?
- I don't like her.

347
00:24:47,230 --> 00:24:49,150
She read too fast and she skipped parts.

348
00:24:49,270 --> 00:24:50,950
He hired his girlfriend to read for you.

349
00:24:51,070 --> 00:24:52,590
She wasn't one of my girlfriends.

350
00:24:52,670 --> 00:24:54,910
Right. Your girlfriends don't know how to read.

351
00:24:55,030 --> 00:24:57,430
Honey. That's so ridiculous.

352
00:24:57,910 --> 00:24:59,830
Don't start that thing.

353
00:25:01,310 --> 00:25:05,030
Mother used to read for me,
but she finds it hard to breathe now.

354
00:25:05,150 --> 00:25:06,710
What's that sound?

355
00:25:07,190 --> 00:25:08,470
These are...

356
00:25:09,590 --> 00:25:13,910
These are pieces of tile
I keep on me for good luck.

357
00:25:14,070 --> 00:25:15,830
Really? Can I feel?

358
00:25:16,030 --> 00:25:19,790
Yeah. Here. That's a piece of red marble.

359
00:25:20,430 --> 00:25:21,790
And that's...

360
00:25:23,070 --> 00:25:26,150
That's a piece of malachite,
another piece of marble.

361
00:25:26,270 --> 00:25:27,870
Is something wrong?

362
00:25:28,510 --> 00:25:29,430
No.

363
00:25:29,870 --> 00:25:31,230
Are you sure?

364
00:25:32,750 --> 00:25:35,430
Yeah. I'm fine. You can keep those.

365
00:25:35,870 --> 00:25:37,670
- Really? Thank you.
- Feel nice?

366
00:25:37,790 --> 00:25:39,510
Yeah. I like it.

367
00:25:40,830 --> 00:25:42,270
For good luck?

368
00:25:42,830 --> 00:25:44,030
Good luck.

369
00:25:44,910 --> 00:25:45,830
Do you want corn?

370
00:25:45,950 --> 00:25:49,190
- We have to find someone to read for Nina.
- She uses them up like tissue.

371
00:25:49,310 --> 00:25:52,110
I do not. I don't go through like tissue paper.

372
00:25:52,190 --> 00:25:54,710
Does everybody know that Daniel's a tiler?

373
00:25:54,790 --> 00:25:57,150
Maybe he could do our guest bathroom, honey.

374
00:25:57,270 --> 00:25:59,830
Not that sort of tiler. Danny's an artist.

375
00:25:59,910 --> 00:26:02,790
- It's a nice bathroom.
- I restore mosaics.

376
00:26:03,710 --> 00:26:05,230
Interesting.

377
00:26:05,910 --> 00:26:09,110
Yeah. Mr. Tambini, my teacher and mentor...

378
00:26:09,230 --> 00:26:13,070
...said that I have great potential,
potential to be a master tiler.

379
00:26:13,430 --> 00:26:14,350
Fascinating.

380
00:26:14,470 --> 00:26:17,470
- Do you ever do your own work?
- Just restoration at the moment.

381
00:26:17,630 --> 00:26:19,830
- You don't find that limiting?
- Actually, I do.

382
00:26:19,950 --> 00:26:22,150
So, basically you're a repairman.

383
00:26:22,390 --> 00:26:24,990
- Would you like some wine?
- You know, alcohol is poison.

384
00:26:25,110 --> 00:26:26,030
Please!

385
00:26:26,110 --> 00:26:28,150
Karen, you're the Ralph Nader of gastronomy.

386
00:26:28,230 --> 00:26:30,350
I'm just telling you the facts.

387
00:26:30,750 --> 00:26:32,470
I read once where they took a rat...

388
00:26:32,550 --> 00:26:35,350
...and injected him with alcohol
20 times a day for five years.

389
00:26:35,430 --> 00:26:37,430
- You know what it died of?
- Holes?

390
00:26:40,190 --> 00:26:42,390
- I like this guy.
- Why don't you have some parsley?

391
00:26:42,470 --> 00:26:45,590
Karen, please.
We have to find someone to read for Nina.

392
00:26:45,710 --> 00:26:47,390
<i>I'm going to read Anna Karenina.</i>

393
00:26:48,590 --> 00:26:51,350
That is the greatest love story ever written.

394
00:26:51,470 --> 00:26:56,150
- Don't talk about love while I'm eating.
- Father doesn't believe in love.

395
00:26:56,430 --> 00:26:59,270
Daniel's a romantic. I can tell.

396
00:26:59,710 --> 00:27:02,230
You've been in love, haven't you, Danny?

397
00:27:02,670 --> 00:27:04,030
Yes, I have, actually.

398
00:27:04,310 --> 00:27:07,390
You have? What's it like? Tell me.

399
00:27:08,350 --> 00:27:10,230
I'm all pins and needles.

400
00:27:10,750 --> 00:27:12,230
What's it like?

401
00:27:14,030 --> 00:27:15,030
All right.

402
00:27:15,390 --> 00:27:16,630
You know how...

403
00:27:17,470 --> 00:27:19,870
...when you listen to music
playing from another room...

404
00:27:20,030 --> 00:27:22,910
...and you're singing,
because it's a tune that you really love...

405
00:27:23,070 --> 00:27:27,390
...when a door closes or a train passes,
so you can't hear the music anymore...

406
00:27:27,510 --> 00:27:29,390
...but you sing along anyway.

407
00:27:29,670 --> 00:27:32,630
Then, no matter how much time passes...

408
00:27:33,630 --> 00:27:37,950
...when you hear the music again,
you're still in exact same time with it.

409
00:27:39,390 --> 00:27:41,110
That's what it's like.

410
00:27:45,390 --> 00:27:46,550
I think.

411
00:27:51,070 --> 00:27:52,310
Made my wife cry.

412
00:27:54,310 --> 00:27:55,470
Thank you, Daniel.

413
00:27:55,550 --> 00:27:57,950
That's a good introduction
to what I have to tell you.

414
00:27:58,030 --> 00:28:01,430
- I think I'm going to kill myself.
- Irene!

415
00:28:02,190 --> 00:28:04,590
- And then I'm going to kill him.
- Oh, no.

416
00:28:04,670 --> 00:28:07,070
Please, don't keep doing that, Irene.

417
00:28:07,190 --> 00:28:09,990
Must we go through this every night?

418
00:28:10,870 --> 00:28:14,670
Honey, how many times do I have to tell you?
You shoot me, then yourself.

419
00:28:14,750 --> 00:28:16,230
That's how it goes. Me, then you.

420
00:28:16,350 --> 00:28:18,870
- Me, then you.
- Irene.

421
00:28:20,870 --> 00:28:23,310
Don't worry.
Her therapist never gives her bullets.

422
00:28:23,430 --> 00:28:24,910
- Unfortunately.
- Bite me.

423
00:28:25,470 --> 00:28:28,790
- Give her the gun.
- Okay, here, take it.

424
00:28:28,950 --> 00:28:31,550
You know, I got it out of my system,
and I feel much better.

425
00:28:31,670 --> 00:28:33,910
Yes, in the words of John Wilkes Booth.

426
00:28:34,870 --> 00:28:36,830
- She likes to carry it.
- I thought it was real.

427
00:28:36,950 --> 00:28:39,670
Okay, Anna. What was it you wanted to tell us?

428
00:28:41,830 --> 00:28:45,550
She was going to say
that she and I are officially engaged.

429
00:28:45,630 --> 00:28:50,150
Anna, that's wonderful! Congratulations!

430
00:28:50,590 --> 00:28:53,110
- There you go, finally!
- It's about time.

431
00:28:53,710 --> 00:28:55,590
- When will it be?
- We haven't set a date yet.

432
00:28:55,710 --> 00:28:57,150
Congratulations, Eric.

433
00:28:57,590 --> 00:28:58,990
That's so wonderful!

434
00:28:59,150 --> 00:29:01,030
Finally! It's about time.

435
00:29:03,270 --> 00:29:04,590
I could read for you, Nina.

436
00:29:04,670 --> 00:29:06,790
- What?
- I could read for you.

437
00:29:07,630 --> 00:29:09,470
Daniel says he'll read for me!

438
00:29:09,590 --> 00:29:11,430
Is that all right? Can Daniel read for me?

439
00:29:11,550 --> 00:29:13,590
I think that's a wonderful idea. Richard?

440
00:29:14,110 --> 00:29:15,150
I don't care.

441
00:29:16,150 --> 00:29:18,070
<i>"Arriving in Moscow, Levin was surprised...</i>

442
00:29:18,190 --> 00:29:21,710
<i>"... to find the Oblonsky household
in total confusion.</i>

443
00:29:21,790 --> 00:29:24,030
<i>"He was alone, in that he could tell no one...</i>

444
00:29:24,190 --> 00:29:25,790
<i>"... of his plans to marry Kitty.</i>

445
00:29:25,990 --> 00:29:27,070
<i>"At 4:00 that afternoon...</i>

446
00:29:27,190 --> 00:29:29,870
<i>"... Levin got out of the sleigh
at the zoological gardens.</i>

447
00:29:30,430 --> 00:29:32,990
"Well-dressed people,
their hats shining in the sunlight...

448
00:29:33,110 --> 00:29:34,830
"... crowded at the gates.

449
00:29:34,910 --> 00:29:38,190
"Levin walked along the path
leading to the skating lake...

450
00:29:38,270 --> 00:29:40,310
"... and he kept repeating to himself:

451
00:29:40,430 --> 00:29:42,990
"'I must not be excited. I must be quiet.

452
00:29:43,270 --> 00:29:46,110
"'What are you doing? What's the matter?
Be quiet, stupid! '...

453
00:29:46,190 --> 00:29:47,950
"... he said to his heart. "

454
00:29:48,830 --> 00:29:51,990
- It's not working, is it?
- What? What do you mean?

455
00:29:52,230 --> 00:29:54,550
We should be outside.
This takes place in the garden.

456
00:29:54,630 --> 00:29:57,070
- We should be in a garden.
- No.

457
00:29:57,390 --> 00:29:58,510
No, we can't do that.

458
00:29:58,630 --> 00:30:01,470
Why don't you go down to the garden
where Anna works?

459
00:30:01,590 --> 00:30:04,790
- That's a great idea.
- No. I can't leave Mother.

460
00:30:04,870 --> 00:30:07,350
Of course, you can. I'll be fine.

461
00:30:07,710 --> 00:30:08,750
I'll get your coat.

462
00:30:08,830 --> 00:30:11,190
You won't need a coat.
It's a beautiful day. Come on.

463
00:30:11,270 --> 00:30:13,470
Come on, Nina. It'll do you good.

464
00:30:13,670 --> 00:30:15,070
Come on, Nina.

465
00:30:17,150 --> 00:30:20,030
"He had to make an effort,
and reason with himself...

466
00:30:20,150 --> 00:30:22,750
"... that all sorts of people were passing him...

467
00:30:22,870 --> 00:30:24,910
"... and that he himself might've come...

468
00:30:24,990 --> 00:30:26,350
"... just to skate. "

469
00:30:26,430 --> 00:30:28,270
I hear a bee. Do you see it?

470
00:30:28,390 --> 00:30:29,910
No. Must've gone.

471
00:30:30,030 --> 00:30:32,590
"He stepped down,
avoiding any long look at her...

472
00:30:32,710 --> 00:30:34,470
"... as one avoids long looks at the sun... "

473
00:30:34,590 --> 00:30:35,430
A bee.

474
00:30:35,550 --> 00:30:37,750
"But seeing her as one sees the sun...

475
00:30:37,830 --> 00:30:38,710
"... without looking. "

476
00:30:38,790 --> 00:30:40,670
That bee is still around.

477
00:30:41,870 --> 00:30:45,910
- No, there's no bee near you. I promise.
- Yes, there is!

478
00:30:45,990 --> 00:30:48,750
I can hear it better than you.
Get it away from me!

479
00:30:48,830 --> 00:30:51,510
- I can't stand bees!
- Nina, relax.

480
00:30:51,590 --> 00:30:53,390
- There's bees all around me!
- I'm here.

481
00:30:53,470 --> 00:30:55,430
- Just stand still.
- There's bees all over me!

482
00:30:55,550 --> 00:30:58,710
There's nothing around you. Nina, stop it!

483
00:31:01,150 --> 00:31:02,430
I hate bees.

484
00:31:17,150 --> 00:31:19,790
- I'm very, very sorry.
- Why did you bring her here?

485
00:31:19,870 --> 00:31:23,350
- It was your mother's idea.
- She's not comfortable in places like this.

486
00:31:24,030 --> 00:31:26,710
You did say that she should get out more.

487
00:31:26,790 --> 00:31:28,670
Yes, she should, with me.

488
00:31:29,270 --> 00:31:32,070
- Why only with you?
- Because she trusts me, that's why.

489
00:31:32,190 --> 00:31:34,110
I think you treat her like a baby. I'm sorry.

490
00:31:34,230 --> 00:31:36,070
- You wouldn't understand.
- No, I understand.

491
00:31:36,190 --> 00:31:38,550
- Nina and I have a special relationship.
- I understand.

